The binary search algorithm works by dividing the array into two halves at every step, and checking if the target element is present in the left or right half. If the target element is present in the left half, we check if it is less than or equal to the middle element. If it is less than the middle element, we move to the right half; if it is greater than the middle element, we move to the left half. If the target element is not present in the left half, we move to the right half and check if it is less than or equal to the middle element; if it is greater than the middle element, we move to the left half. This process continues until we find the target element or exhaust both halves of the array.

